This relates to #17306: @well1791 @lhecker @jcready

### Background info:

Bluebird's `.catch` supports three different methods of filtering errors:

```javascript
somePromise()
    //By constructor
    .catch(SomeErrorType, e => {
         // e is an instance of SomeErrorType
    })
    //By predicate
    .catch(isSomeErrorType, e => {
        // e is an instance of SomeErrorType
    })
     //By object
    .catch({code: 400}, e => {
       // e is some object with code 400
    })
```

### The Problem

With the current typings, filtering by constructor doesn't infer correctly.  Instead of inferring `e` as an instance of `SomeError`, it's inferred as the `SomeError` constructor itself.  Instead, this currently needs to be written as:

```javascript
somePromise()
    .catch(SomeErrorType, (e: SomeErrorType) => { /* ... */ })
```

which isn't the worst thing ever, but it's certainly an annoyance.  (And, I suspect this is by far the most frequent use of the filters: it certainly is in my code)

The root of the problem seems to be that the constructor case is falling into the overloads for the object case.  Since the object case allows basically anything, the constructor is valid match.  I thought Typescript gave preference to overloads based on order, but this appears to not be the case, at least not in this instance.

### Proposed solution:

The current overloads are structured like:

```typescript
catch<E1 extends Error>(
  filter1: (new (...args: any[]) => E1), //Constructor case
  onReject: (error: E1) => R | PromiseLike<R>
): Bluebird<R>;
 
catch<E1>(
  filter1: ((error: E1) => boolean) | (E1 & object), //Predicate and object case
  onReject: (error: E1) => R | PromiseLike<R>
): Bluebird<R>;
```

(With equivalent versions for multiple filters, and for versions where `onReject` returns a type other than `R`)

I was able to get the inference to work as expected by consolidating these into:

```typescript
catch<E1>(
  filter1: (new (...args: any[]) => E1) | ((error: E1) => boolean) | (object & E1),
  onReject: (error: E1) => R | PromiseLike<R>
): Bluebird<R>;
```

The only downside to this change that I've found is that now *any* constructor is accepted as the first argument, rather than only accepting Error subtypes.  Personally, that's a trade-off that I'm willing to make, but certainly if there's a way to fix this without that compromise, that would be preferred, but after a fair bit of playing with this, I wasn't able to find it.  

---

Also, adds a commit that aliases `caught` as `catch`, without needing duplicate definitions.

